<HEAD>Serrano Sworn in as Congressman from Nation's Poorest District</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moments after being sworn in, Rep. Jose
Serrano, D-N.Y., said the first thing he wants to do in his new job
is go home to the South Bronx and talk to children.
   ``Part of what I want to do is go right back into the classroom
and tell kids all about this experience,'' Serrano said.
   He took the oath of office Wednesday, the 38th anniversary of
his mother's arrival in New York from Puerto Rico to join her
husband and seek a better life.
   ``Let the message go from here today to those children who are
still in the projects and who are on the street corner that there
is a better tomorrow,'' Serrano told the House of Representatives
after the swearing-in.
   He was joined on the House floor with three of his five
children. His wife, Mary, brother, other children and about 200
campaign workers stood in the gallery and cheered.
   Serrano, 46, won a landslide victory in a special election March
20 to fill the seat vacated in January when Rep. Robert Garcia,
D-N.Y., resigned. Garcia was convicted of accepting bribes in the
Wedtech influence-peddling scandal.
   Serrano is the only voting Puerto Rican-born member of Congress.
His swearing-in came one day after Susan Molinari, a Staten Island
Republican, took her oath of office. At 32, she is the youngest
member of Congress.
</TEXT>
