</TEXT>
<HEAD>Outspoken Civil Rights Champion to Retire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. George W. Crockett Jr., D-Mich., who came
to Congress at age 70 after a controversial career as civil rights
attorney and judge, says he will retire after his term expires next
year.
   ``There is a time ... when each man or woman must decide to
leave the day-to-day struggle to others,'' the 80-year-old chairman
of the House Western Hemisphere Affairs Subcommittee said Wednesday.
   Crockett had announced his candidacy for a sixth term but faced
at least two challengers for the Democratic nomination in his
predominantly black Detroit district, which could be eliminated as
districts are reapportioned in 1992.
   He said in an interview the prospect of a tough campaign did not
influence his change of heart. ``I've just gotten older and
wiser,'' he said.
   Crockett recently became the first member of Congress to
advocate decriminalizing drug use, the latest of many stands that
outraged conservatives and even made some fellow liberals uneasy.
   He gained national attention in 1949 for his spirited defense of
11 avowed communists charged with subversion in New York. His
clashes with the presiding judge landed him and four other defense
lawyers in prison for four months on contempt charges.
</TEXT>
